<font color="#FF0000">EXPECTATIONS OF RAELENE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul 28 23:07:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hi my name is Nancy and I am working with the folks at POV to help moderate the discussions that we've been having on-line about &quot;Girls Like Us.&quot;  I've been checking in on some of the other discussion forums so perhaps you've seen my posts there.  It seems like a number of people here feel that as a mother, Raelene can choose to have a different kind of family where boys and girls aren't unfairly subjected to different rules and expectations when it comes to taking care of the house, chores, etc.  One person pointed out that the family decisions about who does what don't always break down along gender lines--parents can assign different roles to their kids for all sorts reasons.<br><br>
One thing that I wonder about is whether we're being unfair to Raelene by expecting her to be responsible for changing things by raising her kids differently. Does this play in to the very same 'women do too much of the work and are expected to fix all of the problems' attitude that Raelene seems to be talking about?  What do you think? 
<p><code>--   (Nancy) </code><p>


